  "prompt": "What hand drawn anime is out there?",
  "response": "There are numerous hand-drawn (traditionally animated) anime that are popular and well-regarded. Here are some noteworthy titles across various genres:\n\n1. **Studio Ghibli Films**: Almost all Studio Ghibli movies are hand-drawn and are celebrated for their beautiful animation.\n\n   - *Spirited Away*\n   - *My Neighbor Totoro*\n   - *Princess Mononoke*\n   - *Howl's Moving Castle*\n\n2. **Akira** (1988): A landmark film in anime history, known for its meticulous animation and complex story.\n\n3. **Neon Genesis Evangelion** (1995-1996): A highly influential series in the mecha genre with a mix of traditional animation techniques.\n\n4. **Cowboy Bebop** (1998): Known for its stylish design and smooth animation, this series blends elements of science fiction and noir.\n\n5. **Sailor Moon** (1992-1997): A classic magical girl series that has had a significant impact on anime culture worldwide.\n\n6. **Dragon Ball Z** (1989-1996): A staple of shonen anime, featuring numerous memorable battles and characters.\n\n7. **One Piece** (1999-present): Although it has transitioned over time, the ongoing series began with hand-drawn animation, capturing the adventurous spirit of the manga.\n\n8. **Attack on Titan** (2013-2023): While it incorporates digital techniques, its distinctive style and detailed art draw heavily on traditional methods.\n\n9. **Naruto** (2002-2007) and **Naruto: Shippuden** (2007-2017): These series, especially in the earlier episodes, rely heavily on hand-drawn animation for their epic ninja fights.\n\n10. **Rurouni Kenshin** (1996-1998): A historical action series known for its high-quality hand-drawn animation and storytelling.\n\n11. **Ghost in the Shell** (1995): A cyberpunk classic with intricate animation and philosophical themes.\n\n12. **Berserk** (1997): The original series is known for its dark tone and hand-drawn animation style, though later adaptations have incorporated more CGI.\n\nThese are just a few examples, and many anime series and films combine traditional hand-drawn methods with digital techniques to create their unique styles.",
